Document: AABB  
Path: godot/classes/class_aabb.rst  
Summary: A 3D axis-aligned bounding box.  

AABB is a 3D axis-aligned bounding box used for spatial calculations and collision detection in Godot. It represents a rectangular volume aligned with the coordinate axes, defined by its position and size. The class provides methods to manipulate and query the box, such as checking for intersections with other shapes or transforming the box in space. AABB is commonly used in physics and spatial partitioning systems to optimize performance by simplifying complex geometry into simpler bounding volumes.
---CHUNK---
Document: AABB  
Path: godot/classes/class_aabb.rst  
Summary: The AABB class represents a 3D axis-aligned bounding box defined by position and size, used for fast overlap tests.  

The AABB built-in Variant type represents an axis-aligned bounding box in a 3D space. It is defined by its position and size, which are Vector3. It is frequently used for fast overlap tests (see intersects()). Although AABB itself is axis-aligned, it can be combined with Transform3D to represent a rotated or skewed bounding box. It uses floating-point coordinates. The 2D counterpart to AABB is Rect2. There is no version of AABB that uses integer coordinates.  

Note: Negative values for size are not supported. With negative size, most AABB methods do not work correctly. Use abs() to get an equivalent AABB with a non-negative size. Key Rule: In a boolean context, an AABB evaluates to false if both position and size are zero (equal to Vector3.ZERO). Otherwise, it always evaluates to true.  

Note: C# API has notable differences; see doc_c_sharp_differences for details.
